06902nam a22010335i 9783110778687DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107786877 a10.1515/97831107786872doi  a(DE-B1597)613555  a(OCoLC)1305515689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a307.76094  aNR 1800qDE-14/sred2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/129177:00aMigration and the European City :bSocial and Cultural Perspectives from Early Modernity to the Present /ced. by Christoph Cornelißen, Beat Kümin, Massimo Rospocher. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VI, 251 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Early Modern and Contemporary European History ,x2629-3730 ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Migration and the European City -- tI. Overviews -- tMigration and Cities Today -- t“Parcours” and Maps -- tII. Communities -- tMigration, Identity, Urban Society -- t(Dis)connecting Mobilities -- tStrangers in the Salon -- tMigration and the Making of the World Capital -- tIII. Policies -- tProve Your Origin -- tWhose Freedom of Movement? -- tVariants, Race Relations, and Trend-Setters -- tIV. Representations -- tThe Sounds of a “Migropolis” -- tMigrations and Super-Diversity in Eighteenth-Century Trieste -- t“Urban Dreaming” -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLooking back over the centuries, migration has always formed an important part of human existence. Spatial mobility emerges as a key driver of urban evolution, characterized by situation-specific combinations of opportunities, restrictions, and fears. This collection of essays investigates interactions between European cities and migration between the early modern period and the present. Building on conceptual approaches from history, sociology, and cultural studies, twelve contributions focus on policies, representations, and the impact on local communities more generally. Combining case-studies and theoretical reflections, the volume’s contributions engage with a variety of topics and disciplinary perspectives yet also with several common themes. One revolves around problems of definition, both in terms of demarcating cities from their surroundings and of distinguishing migration in a narrower sense from other forms of short- and long-distance mobility. Further shared concerns include the integration of multiple analytical scales, contextual factors, and diachronic variables (such as urbanization, industrialization, and the digital revolution).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aEuropäische Geschichte. 4aMigration. 4aMobilität. 4aStadtgeschichte. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aMigration, Mobility, Urban History, European History.1 aAlthammer, Beate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunnström, Pål, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornelissen, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornelißen, Christoph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCreyghton, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDo Paço, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHackett, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKümin, Beat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKümin, Beat, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeggewie, Claus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.